1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,000
Stanford University

2
00:00:07,000 --> 00:00:21,000
I think I mentioned last time that the horizon of a black hole is not a place where anything very dangerous is happening,

3
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:26,000
a place where anything very traumatic would happen to somebody who fell in.

4
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:34,000
In fact, if you take a big black hole, now how big? Let's say really big.

5
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:36,000
Really big black hole.

6
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:42,000
What would you find if you fell through the horizon of the black hole?

7
00:00:42,000 --> 00:00:45,000
The answer is you would find nothing there.

8
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:52,000
It would look exactly like flat space or almost exactly like flat space if the horizon was big enough.

9
00:00:52,000 --> 00:00:55,000
And it would just look like empty space.

10
00:00:56,000 --> 00:01:06,000
Well, that's a little odd because the mathematics that we wrote down looks like it does have something striking going on at the horizon.

11
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:08,000
And tonight I want to resolve that.

12
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:10,000
There's a little bit of mathematics.

13
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:17,000
The mathematics is about at the edge of what I do in this class.

14
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:25,000
It's not terribly hard, but we're going to follow through and unravel

15
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:30,000
what happens very, what the horizon of the black hole is really like.

16
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:32,000
What's going on there?

17
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:36,000
All right, so let's write down the metric of the black hole.

18
00:01:46,000 --> 00:01:53,000
That's the beginning always for the starting point for black holes is to write down a metric.

19
00:01:53,000 --> 00:01:58,000
I usually write d tau squared where tau stands for proper time.

20
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:00,000
I'm going to use the other convention.

21
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:09,000
The other convention is just to change the sign of the whole thing and call it proper distance.

22
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:12,000
I'll explain in a moment.

23
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:19,000
Proper distance squared is just the negative of the proper time between two points.

24
00:02:19,000 --> 00:02:22,000
I'm just doing that partly for variety,

25
00:02:22,000 --> 00:02:28,000
partly because it will keep me sane because I know all of these formulas in this form.

26
00:02:28,000 --> 00:02:34,000
Remember that what we wrote for d tau squared was just something involving dt squared, right?

27
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:35,000
dt squared.

28
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:43,000
In flat space, in fact, it was just dt squared minus dx squared plus dy squared plus dz squared.

29
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:46,000
That was d tau squared.

30
00:02:46,000 --> 00:02:50,000
Notice that it's positive if dt is bigger than d tau.

31
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:52,000
So if we're along a trajectory,

32
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:57,000
the time difference is bigger than the space difference.

33
00:02:57,000 --> 00:03:02,000
For example, if the object was standing perfectly still in space,

34
00:03:02,000 --> 00:03:05,000
then dx would be absolutely zero.

35
00:03:05,000 --> 00:03:11,000
We've defined the proper time, d tau squared, so that it would be positive,

36
00:03:11,000 --> 00:03:14,000
so that the square of it would be positive.

37
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:17,000
But supposing we were studying a space-like distance,

38
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:20,000
the distance between two points at a fixed time.

39
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:26,000
Then, with the original definition, this would be negative.

40
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:28,000
And when we took the square root of it,

41
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:32,000
we would say that the distance between these two points is imaginary.

42
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:35,000
Well, we're going to get stuck one way or another.

43
00:03:35,000 --> 00:03:45,000
If we define the invariant distance so that the square of it is positive for time-like things,

44
00:03:45,000 --> 00:03:49,000
then it's going to be negative for space-like things and vice versa.

45
00:03:49,000 --> 00:03:53,000
So what people do is to use two different conventions.

46
00:03:53,000 --> 00:03:57,000
Just whenever you don't like your convention, you change the sign.

47
00:03:57,000 --> 00:03:59,000
Well, now's the time that I don't like my convention,

48
00:03:59,000 --> 00:04:03,000
so I'm going to change the sign and define ds squared.

49
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:05,000
What does s stand for?

50
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:10,000
Spatial distance rather than time distance.

51
00:04:10,000 --> 00:04:17,000
But it's just the negative of the proper time, or the square of the proper time.

52
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:18,000
All right, it's not a big deal.

53
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:25,000
But let's write down the metric of a Schwarzschild black hole in this notation.

54
00:04:25,000 --> 00:04:33,000
It's 1 minus 2mg over r.

55
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:36,000
Sorry, what am I doing here?

56
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:39,000
ds squared has a minus and then a plus.

57
00:04:39,000 --> 00:04:42,000
We change the sign from the proper time.

58
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:46,000
That's the spatial interval, the opposite.

59
00:04:46,000 --> 00:04:47,000
A minus here.

60
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:50,000
dt squared.

61
00:04:50,000 --> 00:04:53,000
And then, you remember what goes here?

62
00:04:53,000 --> 00:04:59,000
1 over 1 minus 2mg over r.

63
00:04:59,000 --> 00:05:02,000
dr squared.

64
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:06,000
And then another piece here, which I'm going to ignore.

65
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:09,000
This had to do with the angles on the sky.

66
00:05:09,000 --> 00:05:12,000
It was r squared times something I think I called the omega squared.

67
00:05:12,000 --> 00:05:14,000
But let's ignore it for now.

68
00:05:14,000 --> 00:05:17,000
Let's not worry about angular distance on the sky.

69
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:21,000
Let's just worry about time and radial distance.

70
00:05:21,000 --> 00:05:25,000
All right, so this plus a bit more here.

71
00:05:25,000 --> 00:05:31,000
When you're far from the black hole, that means when r is large, large compared.

72
00:05:31,000 --> 00:05:33,000
What's 2mg called?

73
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:35,000
It's the Schwarzschild radius.

74
00:05:35,000 --> 00:05:38,000
It's the Schwarzschild radius of the black hole.

75
00:05:38,000 --> 00:05:44,000
2mg, if I were to put in speeds of light, it would be 2mg over c squared.

76
00:05:44,000 --> 00:05:47,000
Right now, c is equal to 1.

77
00:05:47,000 --> 00:05:49,000
2mg is the Schwarzschild radius.

78
00:05:49,000 --> 00:05:56,000
And if you're far away from the black hole, r being much bigger than the Schwarzschild radius,

79
00:05:56,000 --> 00:05:58,000
then this is negligible.

80
00:05:58,000 --> 00:06:05,000
This is negligible, and it's just dt squared minus dt squared plus dr squared.

81
00:06:05,000 --> 00:06:08,000
Exactly as it would be in flat space.

82
00:06:08,000 --> 00:06:09,000
Plus a bit more.

83
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:12,000
All right, as you get close to the black hole,

84
00:06:12,000 --> 00:06:17,000
you get to the point where r is approximately 2mg.

85
00:06:17,000 --> 00:06:22,000
In other words, a distance more or less the same as the Schwarzschild radius.

86
00:06:22,000 --> 00:06:26,000
And then something rather dramatic happens to these coefficients.

87
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:29,000
This one becomes zero.

88
00:06:29,000 --> 00:06:33,000
And this one, in the denominator, it gets to be zero,

89
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:36,000
but a zero in the denominator means something's infinite.

90
00:06:36,000 --> 00:06:40,000
Sure sounds like something unusual is happening.

91
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:41,000
All right.

92
00:06:41,000 --> 00:06:42,000
Let me...

93
00:06:42,000 --> 00:06:45,000
show you exactly what's happening there.

94
00:06:45,000 --> 00:06:47,000
And it's a great big nothing.

95
00:06:47,000 --> 00:06:49,000
Nothing is happening there.

96
00:06:49,000 --> 00:06:53,000
It's an artifact of the choice of coordinates.

97
00:06:53,000 --> 00:06:55,000
So I'm going to show you some examples.

98
00:06:55,000 --> 00:07:01,000
And then we'll work out in detail what's happening at the horizon of the black hole.

99
00:07:04,000 --> 00:07:07,000
Over here, I want to discuss coordinates.

100
00:07:07,000 --> 00:07:11,000
And for the moment now, I'm only talking about ordinary Cartesian coordinates,

101
00:07:11,000 --> 00:07:14,000
on the plane, on the blackboard.

102
00:07:14,000 --> 00:07:18,000
Let's call them y and x.

103
00:07:18,000 --> 00:07:23,000
Later on, the vertical axis will become the time axis,

104
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:27,000
but for now, the vertical axis is just the y axis.

105
00:07:27,000 --> 00:07:29,000
All right.

106
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:32,000
Now, what's the metric of the xy plane?

107
00:07:32,000 --> 00:07:33,000
That's pretty easy.

108
00:07:33,000 --> 00:07:39,000
That's just ds squared is equal to dx squared plus dy squared.

109
00:07:39,000 --> 00:07:40,000
And...

110
00:07:40,000 --> 00:07:45,000
nothing takes place especially interesting at the origin,

111
00:07:45,000 --> 00:07:47,000
or any place else.

112
00:07:47,000 --> 00:07:50,000
Now let's go to polar coordinates.

113
00:07:50,000 --> 00:07:54,000
Polar coordinates means we characterize a point

114
00:07:54,000 --> 00:07:56,000
by a distance,

115
00:07:56,000 --> 00:08:00,000
which I won't call r, because I don't want to confuse it with this r over here.

116
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:02,000
It's a different thing.

117
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:04,000
Let's call it rho,

118
00:08:04,000 --> 00:08:06,000
the Greek letter rho,

119
00:08:06,000 --> 00:08:08,000
which is sort of like r.

120
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:09,000
And...

121
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:12,000
and what's the other variable?

122
00:08:12,000 --> 00:08:13,000
Theta.

123
00:08:13,000 --> 00:08:14,000
Angle.

124
00:08:18,000 --> 00:08:19,000
Okay.

125
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:21,000
First of all,

126
00:08:21,000 --> 00:08:26,000
what is x in terms of rho and theta?

127
00:08:26,000 --> 00:08:29,000
We'll just drop a perpendicular.

128
00:08:29,000 --> 00:08:33,000
x is equal to rho

129
00:08:33,000 --> 00:08:36,000
times cosine of theta, right?

130
00:08:36,000 --> 00:08:38,000
That's the definition of cosine.

131
00:08:38,000 --> 00:08:42,000
And y is rho sine theta.

132
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:44,000
Everybody agree?

133
00:08:44,000 --> 00:08:45,000
Okay, good.

134
00:08:45,000 --> 00:08:49,000
Now what about the metric in terms of rho and theta?

135
00:08:49,000 --> 00:08:52,000
Supposing we start at this point over here,

136
00:08:52,000 --> 00:08:55,000
and we make a little excursion over to here,

137
00:08:55,000 --> 00:08:58,000
a little differential displacement.

138
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:03,000
And that little differential displacement corresponds to changing r a certain amount.

139
00:09:03,000 --> 00:09:06,000
Let's take the red...

140
00:09:06,000 --> 00:09:11,000
the red line here is dr.

141
00:09:11,000 --> 00:09:13,000
That's dr.

142
00:09:13,000 --> 00:09:15,000
And the other red line here,

143
00:09:15,000 --> 00:09:18,000
how long is that?

144
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:21,000
This distance here is just dr.

145
00:09:21,000 --> 00:09:25,000
But what about the distance perpendicular to it?

146
00:09:25,000 --> 00:09:27,000
Is it d theta?

147
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:28,000
Rho d theta.

148
00:09:28,000 --> 00:09:30,000
Rho d theta.

149
00:09:30,000 --> 00:09:31,000
Rho d theta.

150
00:09:31,000 --> 00:09:34,000
The further away you are,

151
00:09:34,000 --> 00:09:37,000
the bigger a given d theta corresponds to.

152
00:09:37,000 --> 00:09:39,000
So that's rho d theta.

153
00:09:39,000 --> 00:09:41,000
So now, can you write down what the metric is?

154
00:09:41,000 --> 00:09:43,000
Sure you can.

155
00:09:46,000 --> 00:09:49,000
ds squared

156
00:09:49,000 --> 00:09:53,000
is equal to dr squared.

157
00:09:53,000 --> 00:09:54,000
d rho squared.

158
00:09:54,000 --> 00:09:56,000
Sorry, this is d rho.

159
00:09:56,000 --> 00:09:58,000
d rho, not dr.

160
00:09:58,000 --> 00:10:01,000
I told you we save r for over there.

161
00:10:01,000 --> 00:10:03,000
d rho, d rho squared,

162
00:10:04,000 --> 00:10:09,000
plus rho squared d theta squared.

163
00:10:09,000 --> 00:10:14,000
That's the metric in polar coordinates.

164
00:10:14,000 --> 00:10:17,000
Notice it has a funny property.

165
00:10:17,000 --> 00:10:20,000
The funny property, nothing gets infinite in this metric,

166
00:10:20,000 --> 00:10:22,000
but notice there's a funny property

167
00:10:22,000 --> 00:10:28,000
that the coefficient of the d theta becomes zero at rho equals zero.

168
00:10:28,000 --> 00:10:32,000
That means moving in theta, you don't get anywhere.

169
00:10:32,000 --> 00:10:33,000
You don't move.

170
00:10:33,000 --> 00:10:35,000
Even if you move in theta.

171
00:10:35,000 --> 00:10:36,000
Well, why not?

172
00:10:36,000 --> 00:10:38,000
Well, because you're just not moving very much

173
00:10:38,000 --> 00:10:42,000
when you move around theta at the origin.

174
00:10:42,000 --> 00:10:44,000
Here's a situation also.

175
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:46,000
This becomes zero,

176
00:10:46,000 --> 00:10:49,000
and it looks like when t changes,

177
00:10:49,000 --> 00:10:52,000
nothing is happening if this is zero.

178
00:10:52,000 --> 00:10:54,000
We'll see as we go along

179
00:10:54,000 --> 00:10:58,000
that they're very, very similar kinds of things.

180
00:10:58,000 --> 00:11:01,000
Okay, everybody understand that?

181
00:11:01,000 --> 00:11:03,000
It's just good old polar coordinates.

182
00:11:03,000 --> 00:11:07,000
But now let's go to Minkowski space,

183
00:11:07,000 --> 00:11:11,000
the space-time of special relativity.

184
00:11:11,000 --> 00:11:15,000
Instead of using y for the vertical axis,

185
00:11:15,000 --> 00:11:19,000
we will now use, let's call it capital T.

186
00:11:19,000 --> 00:11:22,000
I'm not going to call it small t.

187
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:25,000
I'm going to call it capital T.

188
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:29,000
And the horizontal axis I will call x again.

189
00:11:29,000 --> 00:11:32,000
All right, so t is replacing y now.

190
00:11:32,000 --> 00:11:34,000
And what's the metric now?

191
00:11:34,000 --> 00:11:38,000
The metric now is ds squared

192
00:11:38,000 --> 00:11:42,000
is equal to minus dt squared

193
00:11:42,000 --> 00:11:45,000
plus dx squared.

194
00:11:45,000 --> 00:11:46,000
This is just two-dimensional now.

195
00:11:46,000 --> 00:11:48,000
We don't need the other dimensions for this argument

196
00:11:48,000 --> 00:11:50,000
to explain what's happening here.

197
00:11:50,000 --> 00:11:54,000
Just minus dt squared plus dx squared.

198
00:11:54,000 --> 00:11:57,000
The minus is there for special relativity.

199
00:11:57,000 --> 00:11:58,000
Okay?

200
00:11:58,000 --> 00:12:01,000
So that's our metric.

201
00:12:01,000 --> 00:12:03,000
It looks sort of like this,

202
00:12:03,000 --> 00:12:06,000
but only a sign change.

203
00:12:06,000 --> 00:12:11,000
All right, I'm going to now introduce

204
00:12:11,000 --> 00:12:13,000
polar coordinates,

205
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:16,000
but they're called hyperbolic polar coordinates.

206
00:12:16,000 --> 00:12:18,000
Let's just draw in here the light cones.

207
00:12:18,000 --> 00:12:21,000
These are the light cones that light rays move along

208
00:12:21,000 --> 00:12:23,000
that go through the origin.

209
00:12:23,000 --> 00:12:25,000
We're going to introduce, again,

210
00:12:25,000 --> 00:12:28,000
a radial line.

211
00:12:28,000 --> 00:12:30,000
We're going to introduce a radial variable,

212
00:12:30,000 --> 00:12:31,000
or a rho,

213
00:12:31,000 --> 00:12:33,000
which measures distance from the origin,

214
00:12:33,000 --> 00:12:35,000
but not ordinary distance,

215
00:12:35,000 --> 00:12:40,000
proper distance from the origin,

216
00:12:40,000 --> 00:12:43,000
and a time variable that I'm going to call omega.

217
00:12:43,000 --> 00:12:45,000
Here's the relationship.

218
00:12:45,000 --> 00:12:49,000
Here's the definitions.

219
00:12:49,000 --> 00:12:52,000
x, all right, go up to the top there.

220
00:12:52,000 --> 00:12:55,000
x equals rho cosine theta.

221
00:12:55,000 --> 00:12:58,000
We're going to replace that by x equals rho.

222
00:12:58,000 --> 00:13:00,000
That's not cosine theta,

223
00:13:00,000 --> 00:13:01,000
but not theta.

224
00:13:01,000 --> 00:13:04,000
We'll call it omega.

225
00:13:04,000 --> 00:13:08,000
That's a standard terminology for a hyperbolic angle.

226
00:13:08,000 --> 00:13:10,000
I'm going to tell you more about hyperbolic angles

227
00:13:10,000 --> 00:13:12,000
as we go along, if you've forgotten,

228
00:13:12,000 --> 00:13:15,000
but let's just write down the equations on the blackboard.

229
00:13:15,000 --> 00:13:16,000
But this isn't right.

230
00:13:16,000 --> 00:13:17,000
I left out something.

231
00:13:17,000 --> 00:13:18,000
What did I leave out?

232
00:13:18,000 --> 00:13:21,000
Rho.

233
00:13:21,000 --> 00:13:24,000
Completely parallel to what I've written up there.

234
00:13:24,000 --> 00:13:28,000
And t is equal to rho times the hyperbolic sine,

235
00:13:28,000 --> 00:13:31,000
of omega.

236
00:13:31,000 --> 00:13:34,000
All right, now, what are hyperbolic sine and cosine?

237
00:13:34,000 --> 00:13:36,000
Well, whatever they are,

238
00:13:36,000 --> 00:13:39,000
let's come back to cosine and sine.

239
00:13:39,000 --> 00:13:44,000
Cosine squared plus sine squared equals one.

240
00:13:44,000 --> 00:13:49,000
That's a statement of basically Pythagorean theorem,

241
00:13:49,000 --> 00:13:52,000
that this side squared plus that side squared is that side,

242
00:13:52,000 --> 00:13:55,000
is the hypotenuse squared for a unit triangle.

243
00:13:55,000 --> 00:13:57,000
How about for these hyperbolic guys?

244
00:13:57,000 --> 00:13:59,000
What's the equation for them?

245
00:13:59,000 --> 00:14:03,000
Cos squared minus sin squared.

246
00:14:03,000 --> 00:14:11,000
Cos squared omega minus sin squared omega equals one.

247
00:14:11,000 --> 00:14:12,000
All right, that's one thing.

248
00:14:12,000 --> 00:14:18,000
And let me tell you what cos and sin mean.

249
00:14:18,000 --> 00:14:20,000
From the diagram up above,

250
00:14:20,000 --> 00:14:24,000
we can think of this by first drawing a circle,

251
00:14:24,000 --> 00:14:26,000
by first drawing a unit circle,

252
00:14:26,000 --> 00:14:28,000
draw a unit circle,

253
00:14:28,000 --> 00:14:32,000
draw the angle theta,

254
00:14:32,000 --> 00:14:38,000
and then x is given in terms of cosine.

255
00:14:38,000 --> 00:14:41,000
For unit circle, it's just x is equal to cosine,

256
00:14:41,000 --> 00:14:43,000
y is equal to sine.

257
00:14:43,000 --> 00:14:46,000
We do the same thing, except not with a circle,

258
00:14:46,000 --> 00:14:48,000
but with a hyperbola.

259
00:14:48,000 --> 00:14:50,000
We take the hyperbola,

260
00:14:50,000 --> 00:14:53,000
let's, okay, let's raise this up.

261
00:14:53,000 --> 00:14:55,000
Let's take the hyperbola,

262
00:14:55,000 --> 00:14:58,000
not x squared plus y squared equals one,

