1034
00:59:47,000 --> 00:59:52,000
One of the things we did was to calculate the change in energy

1035
00:59:52,000 --> 00:59:54,000
if we drop in one bit.

1036
00:59:54,000 --> 00:59:56,000
Again, remember what a bit means?

1037
00:59:56,000 --> 00:59:59,000
A bit means a photon whose wavelength is comparable

1038
00:59:59,000 --> 01:00:02,000
to the hole size of a black hole.

1039
01:00:02,000 --> 01:00:05,000
How much does the energy change?

1040
01:00:05,000 --> 01:00:07,000
Now, I also told you last time

1041
01:00:07,000 --> 01:00:10,000
that the definition of temperature,

1042
01:00:10,000 --> 01:00:12,000
let's just go back a step,

1043
01:00:12,000 --> 01:00:14,000
temperature seems like a naive,

1044
01:00:14,000 --> 01:00:19,000
naive meaning to say an easily understood concept.

1045
01:00:22,000 --> 01:00:25,000
You feel it with your fingers on the table here.

1046
01:00:25,000 --> 01:00:28,000
You measure it with thermometers.

1047
01:00:28,000 --> 01:00:30,000
We all know what it means.

1048
01:00:30,000 --> 01:00:32,000
But in fact, it's an extremely subtle

1049
01:00:32,000 --> 01:00:35,000
and somewhat derived concept.

1050
01:00:36,000 --> 01:00:40,000
Entropy is an extremely confusing thing.

1051
01:00:40,000 --> 01:00:43,000
When people go to learn thermodynamics for the first time,

1052
01:00:43,000 --> 01:00:44,000
entropy is thrown at them.

1053
01:00:44,000 --> 01:00:46,000
They say, what the hell is that?

1054
01:00:46,000 --> 01:00:49,000
In fact, entropy is very, very basic,

1055
01:00:49,000 --> 01:00:51,000
and in some sense, simple.

1056
01:00:52,000 --> 01:00:54,000
Energy and entropy are really the basis

1057
01:00:54,000 --> 01:00:58,000
for thermodynamics or for statistical mechanics.

1058
01:00:58,000 --> 01:01:00,000
Temperature is a derived concept.

1059
01:01:00,000 --> 01:01:02,000
What is entropy?

1060
01:01:02,000 --> 01:01:04,000
Well, whatever it is, it comes in bits.

1061
01:01:04,000 --> 01:01:05,000
It has to do with information.

1062
01:01:05,000 --> 01:01:08,000
It has to do with yes-no questions.

1063
01:01:08,000 --> 01:01:13,000
Energy, let's suppose we all knew what energy was,

1064
01:01:13,000 --> 01:01:18,000
which I suspect most of us have some idea.

1065
01:01:18,000 --> 01:01:21,000
So we have entropy and energy.

1066
01:01:21,000 --> 01:01:23,000
The definition of temperature

1067
01:01:23,000 --> 01:01:29,000
is simply the energy that's liberated,

1068
01:01:29,000 --> 01:01:32,000
the energy change in a system

1069
01:01:32,000 --> 01:01:35,000
when you add one bit of information to it,

1070
01:01:35,000 --> 01:01:38,000
the minimum change of energy when you add one bit.

1071
01:01:38,000 --> 01:01:40,000
I say minimum.

1072
01:01:40,000 --> 01:01:44,000
The nice analog is the computer.

1073
01:01:44,000 --> 01:01:47,000
You want to erase a bit of information from your computer.

1074
01:01:47,000 --> 01:01:49,000
That bit of information has to go someplace.

1075
01:01:49,000 --> 01:01:50,000
It can't disappear.

1076
01:01:50,000 --> 01:01:52,000
It goes out into the atmosphere,

1077
01:01:53,000 --> 01:01:58,000
and it doesn't necessarily add a certain amount of energy to the atmosphere.

1078
01:01:58,000 --> 01:02:02,000
Of course, if you are sloppy in erasing the bit,

1079
01:02:02,000 --> 01:02:06,000
you know, you do it with a sledgehammer,

1080
01:02:06,000 --> 01:02:10,000
you can add a lot more energy to the atmosphere than that.

1081
01:02:10,000 --> 01:02:12,000
But if you're very careful,

1082
01:02:12,000 --> 01:02:15,000
of course, you'll also be adding more bits of information,

1083
01:02:15,000 --> 01:02:19,000
but if you're very careful to just erase that bit in a minimal way,

1084
01:02:19,000 --> 01:02:22,000
then the minimum energy that you have to add

1085
01:02:22,000 --> 01:02:26,000
to the atmosphere in that case is called the temperature.

1086
01:02:26,000 --> 01:02:33,000
The energy necessary to change the entropy by one unit.

1087
01:02:33,000 --> 01:02:36,000
Okay, so you keep that definition in the back of your head

1088
01:02:36,000 --> 01:02:38,000
of what temperature is.

1089
01:02:38,000 --> 01:02:40,000
It's energy needed to change,

1090
01:02:40,000 --> 01:02:45,000
or energy liberated when you add one bit to a system.

1091
01:02:45,000 --> 01:02:47,000
Okay, let's go back now,

1092
01:02:47,000 --> 01:02:50,000
and say here we have our black hole.

1093
01:02:50,000 --> 01:02:52,000
We're going to throw in

1094
01:02:52,000 --> 01:02:56,000
a photon whose wavelength is comparable to the size of the black hole.

1095
01:02:58,000 --> 01:03:01,000
And let's calculate the change in energy.

1096
01:03:01,000 --> 01:03:06,000
Well, all we have to know is how much energy one photon of a wavelength,

1097
01:03:06,000 --> 01:03:07,000
here's the wavelength,

1098
01:03:07,000 --> 01:03:09,000
the wavelength is comparable to the Schwarzschild radius,

1099
01:03:09,000 --> 01:03:12,000
let's call it R.

1100
01:03:12,000 --> 01:03:17,000
It's equal to twice the mass times G.

1101
01:03:17,000 --> 01:03:19,000
That's also the wavelength of the photon.

1102
01:03:19,000 --> 01:03:21,000
Looks to me like my wavelength is a little bit long.

1103
01:03:21,000 --> 01:03:23,000
Let's shorten it up a little bit.

1104
01:03:26,000 --> 01:03:28,000
Something like that.

1105
01:03:28,000 --> 01:03:34,000
Alright, so what's the energy of a photon of wavelength lambda?

1106
01:03:34,000 --> 01:03:37,000
Lambda is the usual definition of the wavelength,

1107
01:03:37,000 --> 01:03:39,000
usual symbol for it.

1108
01:03:39,000 --> 01:03:41,000
What's the energy of it?

1109
01:03:41,000 --> 01:03:46,000
The energy of it is Planck's constant divided by lambda,

1110
01:03:46,000 --> 01:03:48,000
and now there's a speed of light,

1111
01:03:48,000 --> 01:03:49,000
and the speed of light is in the numerator.

1112
01:03:49,000 --> 01:03:51,000
For the moment, I'm going to keep the constant.

1113
01:03:51,000 --> 01:03:54,000
Later on today, tonight, we're going to throw away the constants,

1114
01:03:54,000 --> 01:03:56,000
or not throw them away,

1115
01:03:56,000 --> 01:03:59,000
but we'll work in units in which they're equal to one.

1116
01:03:59,000 --> 01:04:01,000
I'll just...

1117
01:04:01,000 --> 01:04:04,000
I get bored carrying them around,

1118
01:04:04,000 --> 01:04:06,000
but let's keep them for the time being.

1119
01:04:06,000 --> 01:04:09,000
Alright, H times C divided by lambda.

1120
01:04:09,000 --> 01:04:11,000
Let's just check if it makes sense.

1121
01:04:11,000 --> 01:04:16,000
The energy of a photon when Planck's constant is,

1122
01:04:16,000 --> 01:04:19,000
goes to zero, gets smaller and smaller.

1123
01:04:19,000 --> 01:04:20,000
That makes sense.

1124
01:04:21,000 --> 01:04:24,000
A single photon has a tiny bit of energy.

1125
01:04:24,000 --> 01:04:26,000
Why does it have a tiny bit of energy?

1126
01:04:26,000 --> 01:04:28,000
Because Planck's constant is so small.

1127
01:04:28,000 --> 01:04:32,000
It's also true that as the wavelength gets long,

1128
01:04:32,000 --> 01:04:34,000
the energy of a photon goes down.

1129
01:04:34,000 --> 01:04:37,000
Long wavelength photons have low energy,

1130
01:04:37,000 --> 01:04:40,000
short wavelength photons have high energy.

1131
01:04:40,000 --> 01:04:43,000
And the speed of light, you can just check that it's really got to be there.

1132
01:04:43,000 --> 01:04:46,000
Okay, that's the energy that you add

1133
01:04:46,000 --> 01:04:50,000
when you add one photon which carries one bit.

1134
01:04:51,000 --> 01:04:56,000
Well, the energy to add one bit,

1135
01:04:56,000 --> 01:04:57,000
that's the temperature.

1136
01:04:57,000 --> 01:05:00,000
So this must be the temperature of the black hole.

1137
01:05:00,000 --> 01:05:02,000
And it is.

1138
01:05:02,000 --> 01:05:04,000
When I say it's the temperature,

1139
01:05:04,000 --> 01:05:07,000
I mean within a factor of maybe there's twos and pies,

1140
01:05:07,000 --> 01:05:13,000
because we're not keeping track of detailed numerical constants.

1141
01:05:13,000 --> 01:05:18,000
I'll tell you the numerical constants later if you want.

1142
01:05:18,000 --> 01:05:20,000
The temperature is

1143
01:05:20,000 --> 01:05:23,000
hc over lambda.

1144
01:05:23,000 --> 01:05:25,000
Oh, since I'm keeping track, for the moment,

1145
01:05:25,000 --> 01:05:27,000
for the moment since I'm keeping track of constants,

1146
01:05:27,000 --> 01:05:29,000
I've left something out of here.

1147
01:05:29,000 --> 01:05:31,000
c squared.

1148
01:05:31,000 --> 01:05:34,000
Speed of light squared, yeah.

1149
01:05:34,000 --> 01:05:36,000
Alright, so that's the temperature.

1150
01:05:36,000 --> 01:05:40,000
But remember that lambda is supposed to be chosen

1151
01:05:40,000 --> 01:05:42,000
equal to the size of the black hole.

1152
01:05:42,000 --> 01:05:44,000
So let's put that in.

1153
01:05:44,000 --> 01:05:48,000
Either r or hc over lambda.

1154
01:05:48,000 --> 01:05:55,000
hc over twice mg

1155
01:05:55,000 --> 01:05:58,000
and another c squared in the numerator.

1156
01:05:58,000 --> 01:06:02,000
So Planck's constant times c cubed.

1157
01:06:02,000 --> 01:06:04,000
And we can't trust this factor of two.

1158
01:06:04,000 --> 01:06:06,000
The factor of two is not trustworthy.

1159
01:06:06,000 --> 01:06:08,000
I'll tell you what the right answer is in a minute.

1160
01:06:08,000 --> 01:06:12,000
hc cubed divided by the mass times g.

1161
01:06:12,000 --> 01:06:14,000
Notice one curious thing.

1162
01:06:14,000 --> 01:06:17,000
That as the mass gets bigger and bigger,

1163
01:06:18,000 --> 01:06:21,000
it's not going to be equal to the mass times g.

1164
01:06:21,000 --> 01:06:23,000
Oh, several things.

1165
01:06:23,000 --> 01:06:25,000
First thing.

1166
01:06:25,000 --> 01:06:27,000
h appears there.

1167
01:06:27,000 --> 01:06:30,000
That means that the temperature of the black hole

1168
01:06:30,000 --> 01:06:32,000
is a quantum effect.

1169
01:06:32,000 --> 01:06:37,000
It would be zero if h bar of Planck's constant was zero.

1170
01:06:37,000 --> 01:06:40,000
So it's a thing which only happens

1171
01:06:40,000 --> 01:06:43,000
because Planck's constant is not zero.

1172
01:06:43,000 --> 01:06:45,000
It's another way of saying

1173
01:06:45,000 --> 01:06:47,000
it's there because of quantum mechanics.

1174
01:06:47,000 --> 01:06:52,000
c cubed, well, it's there for dimensional reasons.

1175
01:06:52,000 --> 01:06:55,000
The mass is in the denominator.

1176
01:06:55,000 --> 01:06:57,000
That's interesting.

1177
01:06:57,000 --> 01:06:59,000
The bigger the mass of the black hole,

1178
01:06:59,000 --> 01:07:01,000
the colder it is.

1179
01:07:01,000 --> 01:07:04,000
Now that's a little bit odd for the following reason.

1180
01:07:04,000 --> 01:07:06,000
Mass is energy.

1181
01:07:06,000 --> 01:07:08,000
E equals mc squared.

1182
01:07:08,000 --> 01:07:11,000
So energy and mass are the same thing.

1183
01:07:11,000 --> 01:07:12,000
You're used to the idea

1184
01:07:12,000 --> 01:07:16,000
when you add energy to something, it gets hotter.

1185
01:07:16,000 --> 01:07:21,000
A black hole gets cooler when you add energy to it.

1186
01:07:21,000 --> 01:07:24,000
The bigger its mass, the cooler it is.

1187
01:07:24,000 --> 01:07:26,000
That's got an odd consequence.

1188
01:07:26,000 --> 01:07:28,000
We'll come to that odd consequence in a moment,

1189
01:07:28,000 --> 01:07:30,000
but let's just keep track of it.

1190
01:07:30,000 --> 01:07:32,000
This is the temperature of the black hole.

1191
01:07:32,000 --> 01:07:35,000
I'll give you the right formula now.

1192
01:07:35,000 --> 01:07:37,000
If I write it in terms of h bar,

1193
01:07:37,000 --> 01:07:41,000
then I know the answer, and it's 8 pi.

1194
01:07:41,000 --> 01:07:44,000
That's the actual correct answer.

1195
01:07:44,000 --> 01:07:46,000
h bar times c cubed,

1196
01:07:46,000 --> 01:07:50,000
divided by 8 pi times mass times Newton's constant.

1197
01:07:52,000 --> 01:07:54,000
Okay, first question.

1198
01:07:54,000 --> 01:07:58,000
How hot is a real solar mass black hole?

1199
01:07:58,000 --> 01:08:01,000
So for that we would stick in a mass,

1200
01:08:01,000 --> 01:08:04,000
what's the mass of a solar mass?

1201
01:08:04,000 --> 01:08:07,000
10 to the 30th kilograms or something.

1202
01:08:07,000 --> 01:08:09,000
There's a big number downstairs.

1203
01:08:09,000 --> 01:08:11,000
g is a small number.

1204
01:08:11,000 --> 01:08:14,000
c cubed is huge, and h bar is teeny, teeny, teeny.

1205
01:08:14,000 --> 01:08:16,000
So some people might say,

1206
01:08:16,000 --> 01:08:20,000
well, there's some competition of big numbers and small numbers.

1207
01:08:20,000 --> 01:08:24,000
But the final answer is that this is a small number.

1208
01:08:24,000 --> 01:08:26,000
But not that small.

1209
01:08:26,000 --> 01:08:28,000
Well, it's small.

1210
01:08:28,000 --> 01:08:30,000
This is about, for a solar mass black hole,

1211
01:08:30,000 --> 01:08:33,000
for a black hole of stellar mass,

1212
01:08:33,000 --> 01:08:38,000
this is about 10 to the minus 8 Kelvin.

1213
01:08:38,000 --> 01:08:40,000
So it's colder than anything.

1214
01:08:40,000 --> 01:08:44,000
Let's see, is it colder than anything in the...

1215
01:08:44,000 --> 01:08:46,000
People talk about getting down to nano-Kelvins

1216
01:08:46,000 --> 01:08:49,000
for some reasons or other, so...

1217
01:08:49,000 --> 01:08:53,000
Maybe things in laboratories are actually colder than this.

1218
01:08:53,000 --> 01:08:55,000
But this is damn cold.

1219
01:08:55,000 --> 01:08:56,000
Okay?

1220
01:08:56,000 --> 01:09:02,000
It's so cold that it's much, much colder than empty space.

1221
01:09:02,000 --> 01:09:06,000
Even in the remotest regions of the universe

1222
01:09:06,000 --> 01:09:10,000
where they're far, far from any stars or anything else,

1223
01:09:10,000 --> 01:09:13,000
we know that the temperature of empty space,

1224
01:09:13,000 --> 01:09:17,000
to the extent that empty space, that space is empty,

1225
01:09:17,000 --> 01:09:21,000
ordinary empty space, is about 3 degrees Kelvin.

1226
01:09:21,000 --> 01:09:24,000
That's the microwave background.

1227
01:09:24,000 --> 01:09:26,000
And so the black hole is...

1228
01:09:26,000 --> 01:09:32,000
This black hole is colder than anything in empty space.

1229
01:09:32,000 --> 01:09:35,000
That means even if you had such a black hole,

1230
01:09:35,000 --> 01:09:38,000
which there was nothing else around to fall into it,

1231
01:09:38,000 --> 01:09:42,000
even if you managed to create a black hole

1232
01:09:42,000 --> 01:09:46,000
in otherwise completely empty space,

1233
01:09:46,000 --> 01:09:50,000
the empty space around it would be hotter than it is.

1234
01:09:50,000 --> 01:09:55,000
What happens when you take a cold object and put it in a hot bath?

1235
01:09:56,000 --> 01:10:03,000
Heat flows from the warm region to the cold region.

1236
01:10:03,000 --> 01:10:07,000
Another way of saying it is the black hole simply swallows up

1237
01:10:07,000 --> 01:10:09,000
the microwave radiation.

1238
01:10:09,000 --> 01:10:11,000
It just sucks it in.

1239
01:10:11,000 --> 01:10:14,000
But you can also just think of it as the flow of heat

1240
01:10:14,000 --> 01:10:16,000
from warm to cold.

1241
01:10:16,000 --> 01:10:19,000
Okay, what happens now?

1242
01:10:19,000 --> 01:10:23,000
What happens if I'm in outer space and I'm cold,

1243
01:10:23,000 --> 01:10:28,000
but somebody brings a heater and warms me up?

1244
01:10:28,000 --> 01:10:31,000
I get warmer, right, if I absorb some heat.

1245
01:10:31,000 --> 01:10:34,000
Now let's think about what happens to the black hole.

1246
01:10:34,000 --> 01:10:38,000
The black hole absorbs some heat from its surroundings.

1247
01:10:38,000 --> 01:10:39,000
What happens to its mass if it absorbs some heat?

1248
01:10:39,000 --> 01:10:40,000
It is absorbed.

1249
01:10:40,000 --> 01:10:42,000
It increases.

1250
01:10:42,000 --> 01:10:46,000
Its energy increases, but then what happens to its temperature?

1251
01:10:46,000 --> 01:10:47,000
It goes down.

1252
01:10:47,000 --> 01:10:49,000
It gets even colder.

1253
01:10:49,000 --> 01:10:50,000
It gets even colder.

1254
01:10:50,000 --> 01:10:52,000
What happens when it gets even colder?

1255
01:10:52,000 --> 01:10:57,000
It even becomes more efficient at absorbing heat.

1256
01:10:57,000 --> 01:11:00,000
But it absorbs heat and it gets colder.

1257
01:11:00,000 --> 01:11:01,000
Catch 22.

1258
01:11:01,000 --> 01:11:04,000
The more it absorbs heat, the colder it gets.

1259
01:11:04,000 --> 01:11:07,000
But let's imagine that we had a black hole,

1260
01:11:07,000 --> 01:11:08,000
I don't know where it came from,

1261
01:11:08,000 --> 01:11:09,000
which happens to be a little bit colder than it is.

1262
01:11:09,000 --> 01:11:16,000
It happens to be a little bit warmer than the surroundings.

1263
01:11:16,000 --> 01:11:18,000
Which way does the heat go?

1264
01:11:18,000 --> 01:11:22,000
Heat goes from the black hole into the atmosphere.

1265
01:11:22,000 --> 01:11:25,000
The black hole loses mass.

1266
01:11:25,000 --> 01:11:28,000
What happens when it loses mass?

1267
01:11:28,000 --> 01:11:31,000
It gets hotter.

1268
01:11:31,000 --> 01:11:34,000
So it's a runaway situation.

1269
01:11:34,000 --> 01:11:37,000
If a black hole is cooler than its environment,

1270
01:11:37,000 --> 01:11:40,000
it will absorb energy and get colder.

1271
01:11:40,000 --> 01:11:43,000
If the black hole is warmer than its environment,

1272
01:11:43,000 --> 01:11:46,000
it will give off energy and get hotter.

1273
01:11:46,000 --> 01:11:48,000
It will just run away.

1274
01:11:48,000 --> 01:11:52,000
As it's running away, of course, and getting hotter,

1275
01:11:52,000 --> 01:11:54,000
its mass is getting smaller and smaller.

1276
01:11:54,000 --> 01:11:56,000
Sort of an explosive situation.

1277
01:11:56,000 --> 01:11:58,000
Its mass gets smaller and smaller.

1278
01:11:58,000 --> 01:11:59,000
It gets hotter and hotter.

1279
01:11:59,000 --> 01:12:02,000
And eventually gets so hot that it just explodes.

1280
01:12:02,000 --> 01:12:06,000
If it runs in that direction.

1281
01:12:07,000 --> 01:12:14,000
So a black hole in thermal equilibrium with its environment

1282
01:12:14,000 --> 01:12:16,000
is unstable.

1283
01:12:16,000 --> 01:12:21,000
Even if it had exactly the same temperature as its environment,

1284
01:12:21,000 --> 01:12:23,000
a fluctuation could happen.

1285
01:12:23,000 --> 01:12:26,000
By accident, just by random fluctuation,

1286
01:12:26,000 --> 01:12:29,000
it might absorb a little bit of extra energy.

1287
01:12:29,000 --> 01:12:32,000
If it did so, it would get colder.

1288
01:12:32,000 --> 01:12:35,000
If it got colder, it would be more of an absorber.

1289
01:12:35,000 --> 01:12:36,000
